WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.520
There will be a little bit of deja vu as you see my slides, but I think we'll have the

00:00:04.520 --> 00:00:07.580
opportunity to dive a little bit more deeply into the trial data.

00:00:07.580 --> 00:00:14.520
So I'll be presenting the initial results of Bexobrutidig, and I also struggle to say

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:19.740
the word, the NERCS degrader that's far along in clinical development.

00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:23.740
Admittedly, I have not yet treated a patient with this drug.

00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:29.000
Our site will join their trials going forward, but I have the opportunity to review their

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:29.800
data from ASH.

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:37.200
So this is the molecule, not as a medicinal chemist, I can't say too much, but I sometimes

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:43.240
feel like anything with the same number of circles and nitrogens will bind similarly.

00:00:43.540 --> 00:00:47.840
But the basic idea that one side of it binds to serum line, the other side of it binds

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:52.960
to BTK, and I believe in the ATP binding pocket domain of the BTK molecule.

00:00:55.200 --> 00:00:58.760
I'm not going to address some of these, but I guess the things that they highlight are

00:00:58.760 --> 00:00:59.840
that this is...

00:00:59.840 --> 00:00:59.900
Sorry.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.660
This is something that acts catalytically, so not much of the molecule is needed to maintain

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:04.260
activity.

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:09.200
It has been confirmed to cross blood-brain barrier is the other thing that's sometimes

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:11.020
highlighted in its preclinical testing.

00:01:11.900 --> 00:01:14.500
This is the phase one trial design.

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:21.580
So phase one A was a dose escalation ranging from 50 to 600 milligrams with a cohort specifically

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:25.480
in CLL-SLL and a Waldenstrom's or non-Hodgkin lymphoma cohort.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:29.980
And then a phase one B that was initially based on project optimist testing.

00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:29.980
And then a phase one B that was initially based on project optimist testing.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.060
200 milligram and 600 milligram dose levels, and then 600 milligram dose expansion cohorts

00:01:36.060 --> 00:01:42.460
in various specific clinical contexts, including no mutation or triple refractive disease and

00:01:42.460 --> 00:01:44.320
others, or double refractive disease and others.

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:52.060
I'll focus just on the CLL data for this presentation, although I've seen that the Waldenstrom's

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:55.420
data has been presented in other contexts and looks very promising as well.

00:01:55.860 --> 00:01:59.980
So for the patients with CLL, you can see on the left, the 48 patients.

00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:05.200
Treated in the dose escalation included 16 patients treated at that 600 milligram dose.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:11.100
About a third of them stopped treatment for various reasons, mostly progression, if you

00:02:11.100 --> 00:02:15.560
total up the numbers, and just a few, four of the 22 stopped for adverse event.

00:02:16.420 --> 00:02:24.980
In the phase one B cohort, you can see, I guess, a total of 54 patients treated in the

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:28.760
200 or 600 milligram doses across the different cohorts.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:29.960
Again,

00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:33.960
about a third stopping mostly for progression, and a few for adverse events.

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:41.160
The median follow-up is longer for the phase one A, so a lot of the progression-free survival data

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:47.480
focuses in that cohort. Dr. Erdat presented this, but I think the other thing to highlight is they

00:02:47.480 --> 00:02:52.120
did allow patients with CNS involvement in the trial, and they do document responses in that

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:57.640
group, which I thought was interesting. The adverse events are shown here, and similar to what

00:02:57.640 --> 00:03:02.440
Dr. Erdat said, I think adverse event-wise, I would view this as another BTK inhibitor.

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:09.560
The AEs are largely overlapping with what we're familiar with seeing with BTK inhibitors, maybe

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:15.080
confirming the specificity of its effects. They did have a few grade five events that they all

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:20.600
deemed as not related to the drug, pulmonary embolism, pneumonia, and death for reasons

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:27.480
not specified. And then, as Dr. Erdat showed, excellent activity across different mutational

00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:37.880
characteristics. The overall PFS is, or the median PFS at the moment is, or median duration

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:43.800
response is 20 months. But again, this is at the phase one A cohort, so including patients treated

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:50.040
at lower than the recommended phase two dose. And the phase one A PFS is shown here in Kaplan-Meier

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:57.560
form. Subgroup analyses, as Herb showed, are here. I think that the one thing that,

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:03.160
maybe to highlight, are that the C481S mutations all uniformly responded. You can see nine out of

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:09.400
nine. They had a few patients with other mutations that are shown here with, I guess, less uniform

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:15.880
response. They did not have patients with the A428 mutation, which I think has been identified

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:22.760
as a concerning mutation for this class of drugs. So the conclusions that the authors drew,

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:27.480
and then my thoughts on their further development are shown here. High response rate with

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:32.280
so far, pretty meaningful PFS for a group of patients that may not have other treatment options.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:40.440
So where do we go forward as a field? I'd say both of these drugs are, you'll hear from other

00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:45.000
speakers, are next looking at comparisons to pertobrutinum as far as their registrational

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:50.280
strategies. I think where they'll be most useful to us as physicians and the patients are to

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:56.920
confirm that they work in highly refractory or "triple exposed" cases, where this will be really

00:04:57.400 --> 00:05:03.960
important. And then the other thought I had is how was this drug, or how are the two drugs going

00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:09.960
to differentiate from each other? Are they just two ways of degrading BTK? Over time, we'll be

00:05:09.960 --> 00:05:14.200
learning that there are some small distinctions, perhaps as we saw between the different covalent

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:20.280
BTK inhibitors. But yeah, it will be interesting for the field. I do think right now it's helpful

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:24.920
for both of these drugs to be in development so that patients across the country have option to

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:27.320
this class of drugs. And then the other thought I had is how was this drug going to differentiate

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:30.760
from each other? And I think it would also be helpful for all of us to have perhaps some

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:35.720
firsthand experience treating patients with both these drugs, so we can start to differentiate them

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:38.840
in our experience as well. Thanks so much. Dr. Andy Roark:
